<div id="about" class="tab-content">
		
			
			
				<div class="divider tpad bpad"></div>
				
				<div class="authorbio">
					<div class="image"><img src="http://www.poetryfoundation.org/uploads/authors/87bb0fe164/160x/xphilip-larkin-448.jpg.pagespeed.ic.sczacAzPQ4.jpg" alt=" Philip  Larkin" pagespeed_url_hash="3119320394"/></div>
					<div class="bio image">
							<h3><a href="/bio/philip-larkin">Biography</a></h3>
							<p>Philip Larkin, an eminent writer in postwar England, was a national favorite poet who was commonly referred to as "England's <em>other</em> Poet Laureate" until his death in 1985. Indeed, when the position of laureate became vacant in 1984, many poets and critics favored Larkin's appointment, but the shy, provincial author preferred to avoid the limelight. An "artist of the first rank" in the words of <em>Southern Review</em> contributor John . . . </p>
							<p><strong><a href="/bio/philip-larkin" class="more link">Continue reading this biography</a></strong></p>
					</div>
				</div>
			
		
		<div class="clear"></div>
							<div class="section">
				
						<div class="divider"></div>
						<div class="right backtotop"><a href="#" class="backtotop">back to top</a></div>

						<h3>Poems by Philip  Larkin</h3>
						<ul class="list poem">
							<li><span class="icon l"></span><a href="/poem/177058" class="title">An Arundel Tomb</a></li>		<li><a href="/poem/178058" class="title">Aubade</a></li>		<li><a href="/poem/178046" class="title">Days</a></li>		<li><a href="/poem/178052" class="title">Dockery and Son</a></li>		<li><a href="/poem/178049" class="title">Faith Healing</a></li>	</ul>				
				
					<div class="expander poems">
						<ul class="list poem">
